Dyadic semi-structured interviews were audio-recorded and then summarized by a qualitative methods specialist (QMS) (Jaime Gilliland), based on best practices for rapid qualitative (RA) data analysis. RA was conducted in two phases: a "horizontal" phase and a "vertical" phase.

In the horizontal phase, the QMS reviewed the individual interview summaries, and significant statements were identified based on a priori constructs from the interview guide. Statements were sorted into categories relating to prior experience with exercise and Fitbit devices;

experience participating in the study (Fitbit use, logistics, dyad participation); challenges or issues with study participation; impact of study participation and plans for continued engagement; and recommendations for future studies. In the vertical phase, the QMS and a clinical research coordinator trained in qualitative analysis methods reviewed the statements grouped within each category, across all participants, to identify primary themes. The analytic team collaboratively and iteratively reviewed the data to refine categories and identify themes salient across dyad interviews, and to identify illustrative participant quotations. Themes included prominent sentiments both within each category and across categories, and any notable divergences.
